1. There is no known cure for multiple sclerosis. 
2. There are however, many treatment options for multiple sclerosis. 
3. These treatments are aimed at reducing the frequency and severity of MS exacerbations. 
4. The most common treatment options for MS include: 
5. - "disease-modifying" drugs, which can reduce the frequency and severity of MS attacks, and may also reduce the risk of future attacks; 
6. - "relapsing-remitting" drug therapy, which is used to treat individual attacks of multiple sclerosis and includes corticosteroids during an attack and then a taper back to other therapy; 
7. - physical therapy, which can improve function and reduce disability; 
8. - and, if needed, walkers, canes, braces, and other devices that can help patients maintain mobility and function. 
9. In addition, many people with MS, because of their therapeutic needs, end up taking a combination of the medications listed above. 
10. As for a time frame on a cure, I would not even venture a guess. I would not expect a cure in the next 5 years.

